[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] In Unix-like computer operating systems, a **pipeline** is a mechanism for inter-process communication using message passing.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] A pipeline is a set of processes chained together by their standard streams, so that the output text of each process (*stdout*) is passed directly as input (*stdin*) to the next one.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] The second process is started as the first process is still executing, and they are executed concurrently.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] The concept of pipelines was championed by Douglas McIlroy at Unix's ancestral home of Bell Labs, during the development of Unix, shaping its toolbox philosophy.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] It is named by analogy to a physical pipeline.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] A key feature of these pipelines is their "hiding of internals".
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] This in turn allows for more clarity and simplicity in the system.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] The **pipes** in the pipeline are anonymous pipes (as opposed to named pipes), where data written by one process is buffered by the operating system until it is read by the next process, and this uni-directional channel disappears when the processes are completed.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] The standard shell syntax for anonymous pipes is to list multiple commands, separated by vertical bars ("pipes" in common Unix verbiage).
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] The pipeline concept was invented by Douglas McIlroy and first described in the man pages of Version 3 Unix.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] McIlroy noticed that much of the time command shells passed the output file from one program as input to another.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] His ideas were implemented in 1973 when ("in one feverish night", wrote McIlroy) Ken Thompson added the `pipe()` system call and pipes to the shell and several utilities in Version 3 Unix.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] "The next day", McIlroy continued, "saw an unforgettable orgy of one-liners as everybody joined in the excitement of plumbing." McIlroy also credits Thompson with the `|` notation, which greatly simplified the description of pipe syntax in Version 4.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] Although developed independently, Unix pipes are related to, and were preceded by, the 'communication files' developed by Ken Lochner in the 1960s for the Dartmouth Time-Sharing System.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] This feature of Unix was borrowed by other operating systems, such as MS-DOS and the CMS Pipelines package on VM/CMS and MVS, and eventually came to be designated the pipes and filters design pattern of software engineering.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] In Tony Hoare's communicating sequential processes (CSP), McIlroy's pipes are further developed.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] A pipeline mechanism is used for inter-process communication using message passing.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] In most Unix-like systems, all processes of a pipeline are started at the same time, with their streams appropriately connected, and managed by the scheduler together with all other processes running on the machine.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] An important aspect of this, setting Unix pipes apart from other pipe implementations, is the concept of buffering: for example a sending program may produce 5000 bytes per second, and a receiving program may only be able to accept 100 bytes per second, but no data is lost.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] Instead, the output of the sending program is held in the buffer.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] When the receiving program is ready to read data, the next program in the pipeline reads from the buffer.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] If the buffer is filled, the sending program is stopped (blocked) until at least some data is removed from the buffer by the receiver.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] In Linux, the size of the buffer is 16 pages, equivalent to 65,536 bytes (64 KiB) on most systems.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] Tools like netcat and socat can connect pipes to TCP/IP sockets.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] All widely used Unix shells have a special syntax construct for the creation of pipelines.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] In all usage one writes the commands in sequence, separated by the ASCII vertical bar character `|` (which, for this reason, is often called "pipe character").
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] The shell starts the processes and arranges for the necessary connections between their standard streams (including some amount of buffer storage).
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] The command `ls -l` is executed as a process, the output (stdout) of which is piped to the input (stdin) of the process for `grep key`; and likewise for the process for `less`.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] Each process takes input from the previous process and produces output for the next process via *standard streams*.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] Each `|` tells the shell to connect the standard output of the command on the left to the standard input of the command on the right by an inter-process communication mechanism called an (anonymous) pipe, implemented in the operating system.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] Pipes are unidirectional; data flows through the pipeline from left to right.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] Below is an example of a pipeline that implements a kind of spell checker for the web resource indicated by a URL.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] **`sed`** replaces all characters (from the web page's content) that are not spaces or letters, with spaces.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] **`tr`** changes all of the uppercase letters into lowercase and converts the spaces in the lines of text to newlines (each 'word' is now on a separate line).
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] **`grep`** includes only lines that contain at least one lowercase alphabetical character (removing any blank lines).
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] **`sort`** sorts the list of 'words' into alphabetical order, and the `-u` switch removes duplicates.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] **`comm`** finds lines in common between two files, `-23` suppresses lines unique to the second file, and those that are common to both, leaving only those that are found only in the first file named.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] The `-` in place of a filename causes `comm` to use its standard input (from the pipe line in this case).
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] `sort /usr/share/dict/words` sorts the contents of the `words` file alphabetically, as `comm` expects, and `<( ... )` outputs the results to a temporary file (via process substitution), which `comm` reads.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] The result is a list of words (lines) that are not found in /usr/share/dict/words.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] **`less`** allows the user to page through the results.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] By default, the standard error streams ("stderr") of the processes in a pipeline are not passed on through the pipe; instead, they are merged and directed to the console.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] However, many shells have additional syntax for changing this behavior.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] In the csh shell, for instance, using `|&` instead of `|` signifies that the standard error stream should also be merged with the standard output and fed to the next process.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] The Bash shell can also merge standard error with `|&` since version 4.0 or using `2>&1`, as well as redirect it to a different file.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] In the most commonly used simple pipelines the shell connects a series of sub-processes via pipes, and executes external commands within each sub-process.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] Thus the shell itself is doing no direct processing of the data flowing through the pipeline.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] However, it's possible for the shell to perform processing directly, using a so-called **mill** or **pipemill** (since a `while` command is used to "mill" over the results from the initial command).
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] There are a couple of possible ways to avoid this behavior.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] First, some drains support an option to disable reading from `stdin` (e.g.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] Alternatively, if the drain does not *need* to read any input from `stdin` to do something useful, it can be given `< /dev/null` as input.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] As all components of a pipe are run in parallel, a shell typically forks a subprocess (a subshell) to handle its contents, making it impossible to propagate variable changes to the outside shell environment.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] To remedy this issue, the "pipemill" can instead be fed from a here document containing a command substitution, which waits for the pipeline to finish running before milling through the contents.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] Alternatively, a named pipe or a process substitution can be used for parallel execution.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] GNU bash also has a `lastpipe` option to disable forking for the last pipe component.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] Pipelines can be created under program control.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] The Unix `pipe()` system call asks the operating system to construct a new anonymous pipe object.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] This results in two new, opened file descriptors in the process: the read-only end of the pipe, and the write-only end.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] The pipe ends appear to be normal, anonymous file descriptors, except that they have no ability to seek.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] To avoid deadlock and exploit parallelism, the Unix process with one or more new pipes will then, generally, call `fork()` to create new processes.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] Each process will then close the end(s) of the pipe that it will not be using before producing or consuming any data.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] Alternatively, a process might create new threads and use the pipe to communicate between them.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] Until MacOS Tahoe, the robot in the icon for Apple's Automator, which also uses a pipeline concept to chain repetitive commands together, held a pipe in homage to the original Unix concept.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] C++20 introduces `operator|` (the piping operator) and allows LINQ-style chaining operations with the `std::ranges` namespaces.
[src:nushell/pipeline-unix] `std::views` contains several classes which are invoked through `operator()`.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] An operating system **shell** is a computer program that provides relatively broad and direct access to the system on which it runs.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] The term *shell* refers to how it is a relatively thin layer around an operating system.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Most shells are command-line interface (CLI) programs.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Some graphical user interfaces (GUI) also include shells.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Operating systems provide various services to their users, including file management, process management (running and terminating applications), batch processing, and operating system monitoring and configuration.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Most operating system shells are not *direct* interfaces to the underlying kernel, even if a shell communicates with the user via peripheral devices attached to the computer directly.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Shells are actually special applications that use the kernel API in just the same way as it is used by other application programs.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] A shell manages the user–system interaction by prompting users for input, interpreting their input, and then handling output from the underlying operating system (much like a read–eval–print loop, REPL).
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Since the operating system shell is actually an application, it may easily be replaced with another similar application for most operating systems.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] In addition to shells running on local systems, there are different ways to make remote systems available to local users; such approaches are usually referred to as remote access or remote administration.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Initially available on multi-user mainframes, which provided text-based UIs for each active user *simultaneously* by means of a text terminal connected to the mainframe via serial line or modem, remote access has extended to Unix-like systems and Microsoft Windows.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] On Unix-like systems, Secure Shell protocol (SSH) is usually used for text-based shells, while SSH tunneling can be used for X Window System–based graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:nushell/shell-computing] On Microsoft Windows, Remote Desktop Protocol can be used to provide GUI remote access, since Windows Vista, PowerShell Remote, since Windows 10 build 1809 SSH can also be used for text-based remote access via WMI, RPC, and WS-Management.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Most operating system shells fall into one of two categories – command-line and graphical.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Command-line shells provide a command-line interface (CLI) to the operating system, while graphical shells provide a graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Other possibilities, although not so common, include a voice user interface and various implementations of a text-based user interface (TUI) that are not CLI, such as text-based menu systems.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] The relative merits of CLI- and GUI-based shells are often debated.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Many computer users use both depending on the task to be performed.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Early interactive systems provided a simple command-line interpreter as part of the resident monitor.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] This interpreter might be called by different names, such as `COMCON` on DEC TOPS-10 systems.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] The interpreter would execute one of a number of predefined commands, one of which would be to run a user program.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Common commands would log the user on and off the system, allocate, free, and manipulate devices and files, and query various pieces of information about the system or a user process.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] In 1964, for the Multics operating system, Louis Pouzin conceived the idea of "using commands somehow like a programming language," and coined the term *shell* to describe it.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] In a 1965 document, the shell is defined as "a common procedure called automatically by the supervisor whenever a user types in some message at his console, at a time when he has no other process in active execution under console control.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] This procedure acts as an interface between console messages and subroutine [in the supervisor]." This system was first implemented by Glenda Schroeder and an unnamed man from General Electric.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Multics also introduced the *active function*, a key concept in some later shells.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] In 1971, Ken Thompson developed the Thompson shell in the first version of Unix.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] While simpler than the Multics shell, it contained some innovative features, which have been carried forward in modern shells, including the use of < and > for input and output redirection.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] The graphical shell first appeared in Douglas Engelbart’s NLS system, demonstrated in December, 1968 at the Fall Joint Computer Conference in San Francisco, in what has been called *The Mother of All Demos*.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Engelbart’s colleagues at Stanford Research Institute brought the concept to the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC), where it appeared on the Alto, introduced in 1973.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] From there the idea spread to Niklaus Wirth’s Lilith in 1980, and the Apple Lisa in 1983, then became ubiquitous.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] A command-line interface (CLI) is an operating system shell that uses alphanumeric characters typed on a keyboard to provide instructions and data to the operating system, interactively.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Operating systems such as UNIX have a large variety of shell programs with different commands, syntax and capabilities, with the POSIX shell being a baseline.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Application programs may also implement a command-line interface.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] For example, in Unix-like systems, the telnet program has a number of commands for controlling a link to a remote computer system.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Since the commands to the program are made of the same keystrokes as the data being sent to a remote computer, some means of distinguishing the two are required.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] An escape sequence can be defined, using either a special local keystroke that is never passed on but always interpreted by the local system.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] The program becomes modal, switching between interpreting commands from the keyboard or passing keystrokes on as data to be processed.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] A feature of many command-line shells is the ability to save sequences of commands for re-use.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] A data file can contain sequences of commands which the CLI can be made to follow as if typed in by a user.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Special features in the CLI may apply when it is carrying out these stored instructions.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Such batch files (script files) can be used repeatedly to automate routine operations such as initializing a set of programs when a system is restarted.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Batch mode use of shells usually involves structures, conditionals, variables, and other elements of programming languages; some have the bare essentials needed for such a purpose, others are very sophisticated programming languages in and of themselves.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Conversely, some programming languages can be used interactively from an operating system shell or in a purpose-built program.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Several command-line shells, such as Nushell, Xonsh, Bash (Unix shell), and Z shell, offer command-line completion, enabling the interpreter to expand commands based on a few characters input by the user.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] A command-line interpreter may offer a history function, so that the user can recall earlier commands issued to the system and repeat them, possibly with some editing.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Since all commands to the operating system had to be typed by the user, short command names and compact systems for representing program options were common.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Short names were sometimes hard for a user to recall, and early systems lacked the storage resources to provide a detailed on-line user instruction guide.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] A graphical user interface (GUI) provides means for manipulating programs graphically, by allowing for operations such as opening, closing, moving and resizing windows, as well as switching focus between windows.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Graphical shells may be included with desktop environments or come separately, even as a set of loosely coupled utilities.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Most graphical user interfaces develop the metaphor of an "electronic desktop", where data files are represented as if they were paper documents on a desk, and application programs similarly have graphical representations instead of being invoked by command names.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Graphical shells typically build on top of a windowing system.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] GNOME shell and KDE Plasma are graphical shells for the X Window System and Wayland.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] In the case of macOS, Quartz Compositor acts as the windowing system, and the shell consists of the Finder, the Dock, SystemUIServer, and Mission Control.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Modern versions of the Microsoft Windows operating system use the Windows shell as their shell.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Windows Shell provides desktop environment, start menu, and task bar, as well as a graphical user interface for accessing the file management functions of the operating system.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Older versions also include Program Manager, which was the shell for the 3.x series of Microsoft Windows, and which in fact shipped with later versions of Windows of both the 95 and NT types at least through Windows XP.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] The interfaces of Windows versions 1 and 2 were markedly different.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Desktop applications are also considered shells, as long as they use a third-party engine.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Likewise, many individuals and developers dissatisfied with the interface of Windows Explorer have developed software that either alters the functioning and appearance of the shell or replaces it entirely.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] WindowBlinds by StarDock is a good example of the former sort of application.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] LiteStep and Emerge Desktop are good examples of the latter.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Interoperability programmes and purpose-designed software lets Windows users use equivalents of many of the various Unix-based GUIs discussed below, as well as Macintosh.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] An equivalent of the OS/2 Presentation Manager for version 3.0 can run some OS/2 programmes under some conditions using the OS/2 environmental subsystem in versions of Windows NT.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] A shell can usually also be invoked from within a program through standard system functions like `system()`, `popen()` and `exec()` without any user interface being involved.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Beyond these standard functions, Windows for example provides the "Windows Shell API" which exposes a set of functions that programs can use to interact with the Windows shell.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] These shell functions are provided in DLL's (like shell32.dll and shlwapi.dll) and do not need the default Windows shell GUI i.e. explorer.exe to be running.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Explorer.exe and its replacements generally make use of the Windows Shell API to provide users with a Windows shell GUI without having to implement themselves the Windows shell core functionalities (which are implemented and provided by shell32.dll and shlwapi.dll).
[src:nushell/shell-computing] But programs can use the Windows Shell API for other purposes and without providing users with a shell user interface.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] "Shell" is also used loosely to describe application software that is "built around" a particular component, such as web browsers and email clients, in analogy to the shells found in nature.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] Indeed, the (command-line) shell encapsulates the operating system *kernel*.
[src:nushell/shell-computing] These are also sometimes referred to as "wrappers".
[src:nushell/shell-computing] In expert systems, a shell is a piece of software that is an "empty" expert system without the knowledge base for any particular application.
[src:nushell/www-nushell-sh] Nu works on Linux, macOS, BSD, and Windows.
[src:nushell/www-nushell-sh] Nu pipelines use structured data so you can safely select, filter, and sort the same way every time.
[src:nushell/www-nushell-sh] Stop parsing strings and start solving problems.
[src:nushell/www-nushell-sh] It's easy to extend Nu using a powerful plugin system.
[src:nushell/www-nushell-sh] Nu speaks JSON, YAML, SQLite, Excel, and more out of the box.
[src:nushell/www-nushell-sh] Nu operates on typed data, so it catches bugs that other shells don't.
[src:nushell/www-nushell-sh] Nushell is available as downloadable binaries, via your favourite package manager, in a GitHub Action, and as source code.
[src:nushell/www-nushell-sh] After installing, launch Nu by typing `nu`.
[src:nushell/www-nushell-sh] Join us on Discord if you have any questions about Nu!
[src:nushell/www-nushell-sh] You can help improve this site by giving us feedback or sending a PR.
